# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pacman-arch
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Pacman, a package manager written specifically for Arch Linux, is used to install, remove and update software packages.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] The Arch User Repository (AUR) serves as a community-driven software repository for Arch Linux and provides packages not included in the official repositories and alternative versions of packages; AUR packages can be downloaded and built manually, or installed through an AUR 'helper'.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Arch Linux has comprehensive documentation in the form of a community-run wiki known as the ArchWiki.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Inspired by CRUX, another minimalist distribution, Judd Vinet began the Arch Linux project in March 2002.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] The name was chosen because Vinet liked the word's meaning of "the principal," as in "arch-enemy".
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Originally only for IA-32 (32-bit x86) CPUs, the first x86-64 installation standard ISO image was released in April 2006.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Vinet led Arch Linux until 1 October 2007, when he stepped down due to lack of time, transferring control of the project to Aaron Griffin.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Until Pacman version 4.0.0, Arch Linux's package manager lacked support for signed packages.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Packages and metadata were not verified for authenticity by Pacman during the download-install process.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Without package authentication checking, tampered-with or malicious repository mirrors could compromise the integrity of a system.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Pacman 4 allowed verification of the package database and packages, but it was disabled by default.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] In November 2011, package signing became mandatory for new package builds, and as of March 2012, every official package is signed.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] In June 2012, package signing verification became official and is now enabled by default in the installation process.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] The migration to systemd as its init system began in August 2012, and it became the default on new installations in October 2012.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] It replaced the SysV-style init system, used since the distribution's inception.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] The end of i686 support was announced in January 2017, with the February 2017 ISO being the last one including i686 and making the architecture unsupported in November 2017.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Since then, the community derivative Arch Linux 32 can be used for i686 hardware.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] On 24 February 2020, Aaron Griffin announced that due to his limited involvement with the project, he would, after a voting period, transfer control of the project to Levente Polyak.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] This change also led to a new 2-year term period being added to the Project Leader position.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] In March 2021, Arch Linux developers were thinking of porting Arch Linux packages to x86_64-v3, roughly correlating to the Intel Haswell era of processors.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] In April 2021, Arch Linux installation images began including a guided installation script called 'archinstall' by default.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] In late 2021, the Arch Linux developers released Pacman 6.0, which enabled parallel downloads.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] In February 2022, the Arch Linux developers began offering debug packages.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] In September 2024, Valve partnered with Arch Linux developers to support ongoing development efforts with the focus on build service infrastructure and secure signing enclave.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] On 14 August 2025, the Arch User Repository, the Arch Linux Forums and the Arch Linux website were hit by a distributed denial-of-service attack.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] As a result of the attack web services became temporarily unavailable and downloads from the AUR were severely slowed down or impossible.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Arch is largely based on binary packages.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Packages target x86-64 microprocessors to assist performance on modern hardware.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] A ports/ebuild-like system is also provided for automated source compilation, known as the Arch build system.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] This is largely achieved by encouraging the use of succinctly commented, clean configuration files that are arranged for quick access and editing.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] This has earned it a reputation as a distribution for "advanced users" who are willing to use the command-line interface.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] The current Arch Linux logo was designed by Thayer Williams in 2007 as part of a contest to replace the previous logo.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] The Arch Linux website supplies ISO images that may be burned to a CD or USB drive.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Installation can be accomplished manually by following the instructions on the Arch Wiki, or automatically through the use of the included "archinstall" script.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Another command line utility that comes bundled with the installation media, "pacstrap" may be used to install the base system.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Installation of additional packages which are not part of the base system can be done with either pacstrap, Pacman after booting (or chrooting) into the new installation, or by specifying packages within the guided archinstall script.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] An alternative to using CD or USB images for installation is to use the static version of the package manager Pacman, from within another Linux-based operating system.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] The user can mount their newly formatted drive partition, and use pacstrap (or Pacman with the appropriate command-line switch) to install base and additional packages with the mountpoint of the destination device as the root for its operations.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] This method is useful when installing Arch Linux onto USB flash drives, or onto a temporarily mounted device which belongs to another system.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Depending on the selected installation type, further actions may need to be taken before the new system is ready for use.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Notable configuration includes the installation of a bootloader, configuring the system with a hostname, network connection, language settings, and graphical user interface.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Arch Linux does not schedule releases for specific dates, nor does it provide traditional releases, but instead uses a rolling release model.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Packages in the main repositories are updated often, with new updates being pushed far quicker when compared to long-term support (LTS) distributions.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] This style of package management allows systems to remain updated easily.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Occasionally, manual interventions are needed for certain updates, with instructions posted on the news section of the Arch Linux website.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] All packages are managed through pacman, a package manager written specifically for Arch Linux.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Pacman handles package installation, upgrades, downgrades, removal and features automatic dependency resolution.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] The packages for Arch Linux are obtained from the Arch Linux package tree and are compiled for the x86-64 architecture.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Pacman typically uses binary packages with a `.tar.zst` extension (for zstd compression), with `.pkg` placed before this to indicate that it is a Pacman package (giving `.pkg.tar.zst`); though other compression formats are also valid, such as `.pkg.tar.xz`.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Packages can be installed via `pacman -S *package name*`, and `pacman -Syu` can be used to perform a full system upgrade.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] As well as Arch Linux, Pacman is also used for installing packages under MSYS2 (a fork of Cygwin) on Windows.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Also, *testing* repositories exist which include binary package candidates for other repositories.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] The *core-staging* and *extra-staging* repositories are used for some rebuilds to avoid broken packages in *testing*.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] There are also two other repositories that include the newest version of certain desktop environments.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] The *unstable* repository was dropped in July 2008 and most of the packages moved to other repositories.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] The *community* repository was merged with *extra* in May 2023.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] In addition to the official repositories, there are a number of unofficial user repositories.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] The most well-known unofficial repository is the Arch User Repository, or AUR, hosted on the Arch Linux site.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] The AUR does not host binary packages but instead a collection of build scripts known as PKGBUILDs.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] PKGBUILD scripts are executed by the `makepkg` command, which downloads the necessary files from the software's repository and builds them using the Arch build system.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] The Arch Linux repositories contain both libre and nonfree software, and the default Arch Linux kernel contains nonfree proprietary blobs, hence the distribution is not endorsed by the GNU project.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] The linux-libre kernel can be installed from the AUR or by enabling Parabola's repositories.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] The Arch build system (ABS) is a ports-like source packaging system that compiles source tarballs into binary packages, which are installed via Pacman.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] The Arch build system provides a directory tree of shell scripts, called *PKGBUILDs*, that enable any and all official Arch packages to be customized and compiled.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Rebuilding the entire system using modified compiler flags is also supported by the Arch build system.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] The Arch build system `makepkg` tool can be used to create custom `pkg.tar.zst` packages from third-party sources.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] The resulting packages are also installable and trackable via Pacman.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] For packages not provided in the official repositories, the Arch User Repository (AUR) provides user-made PKGBUILD bash scripts which retrieve and build source code or binaries from non-Arch Linux sources.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] PKGBUILD scripts cannot be downloaded or run by pacman, but they contain all the necessary instructions and metadata to build packages which pacman can install.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Unofficial AUR helper programs, like Yay or Paru, can automate installation from the AUR.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] However, because scripts not validated by any trusted person may be uploaded to the AUR, Arch developers have stated that utilities for automatic finding, downloading and executing of PKGBUILDs, including AUR helpers, will never be included in the official repositories.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Arch Linux directs users to acquaint themselves with the process of vetting PKGBUILDs, including when using AUR helpers.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Instances of malware have been discovered in the past, such as on 19 July 2025 when a modified Firefox build contained a Remote access trojan.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] On 12 June 2026, Arch announced "a high volume of malicious package adoptions and updates in the Arch User Repository", and a list of 1579 affected packages was posted later that day.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] The attack consisted of edits to PKGBUILDs adding installation instructions for malicious npm packages.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Two days later several packages containing obfuscated malware code, russian spam and profanities are also found and fixed.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Package Maintainers, official Arch Linux staff, are charged with "keeping the AUR in working order".
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] They maintain popular packages, communicate with and send patches to developers of packaged software, screen PKGBUILDs for malware, and vote on administrative matters.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Arch Linux is working on making all official packages reproducible.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] This means that when a package is rebuilt in a different environment it should be bit-by-bit identical.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] This allows users and researchers to verify the integrity of the packages found in the official repository.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] The status of this effort can be monitored on the dedicated status page.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] The Arch Linux wiki maintains its own list of Arch-based distributions.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] There are several projects working on porting the Arch Linux ideas and tools to other kernels, including PacBSD (formerly ArchBSD) and Arch Hurd, which are based on the FreeBSD and GNU Hurd kernels, respectively.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Artix Linux is based on Arch, and avoids using systemd.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Instead, users can choose alternatives like OpenRC, runit, s6, and dinit.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Manjaro is an Arch-based distro designed to be easy to use.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Unlike vanilla Arch, Manjaro is designed with both beginners and experienced users in mind.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] EndeavourOS is a terminal-centric distro based on Arch, and the successor of the discontinued Antergos.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Garuda Linux is a gamer-focused distro based on Arch.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] SteamOS 3.0, the version of SteamOS used in the Steam Deck by Valve, is based on Arch Linux.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] CachyOS is a Linux distribution based on Arch Linux with changes and optimizations intended to improve performance on newer hardware, prioritizing gaming, among other tasks.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] As of March 2026, CachyOS is the most popular desktop distro on ProtonDB, overtaking Arch Linux.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] OSNews also has five later reviews about Arch Linux.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] LWN.net wrote a review about Arch Linux in 2005.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] LWN.net also has two later reviews about Arch Linux.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Tux Machines reviewed Arch Linux in 2007.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] Chris Smart from DistroWatch Weekly wrote a review about Arch Linux in January 2009.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] DistroWatch Weekly reviewed Arch Linux again in September 2009 and in December 2015.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] The Linux kernel developer and maintainer Greg Kroah-Hartman (GKH) has stated that he uses Arch Linux and that it "works really really well".
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] He has also praised the Arch Wiki, the distribution's rolling release model, and the feedback loop with the community.
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] In a 2023 DistroWatch poll, about half of the responders maintained that they were running either Arch (17%) or an Arch derivative (30%).
[src:pacman-arch/arch-linux] As of 2025, Arch also enjoys the third highest average rating of any Linux distribution on DistroWatch with a rating of 9.18, with only two higher rated distributions (Artix Linux and BigLinux) also being Arch derivatives.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] There are many thousands of Linux distributions, many based directly or indirectly on other distributions; popular Linux distros include Debian, Fedora Linux, Linux Mint, Arch Linux, and Ubuntu, while commercial distributions include Red Hat Enterprise Linux, SUSE Linux Enterprise, and ChromeOS.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Linux distributions are frequently used in server platforms.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Many Linux distributions use the word "**Linux**" in their name, but the Free Software Foundation uses and recommends the name "**GNU/Linux**", to emphasize the use and importance of GNU software in many distributions.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Other than the Linux kernel, key components that make up a distribution may include a display server (windowing system), a package manager, a bootloader, and a Unix shell.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Linux is one of the most prominent examples of free and open-source software collaboration.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] The Linux kernel is considered by many to be the largest open source project.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] While originally developed for x86-based personal computers, it has since been ported to more platforms than any other operating system, and is used on a wide variety of devices including personal computers, workstations, mainframes, and embedded systems.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Linux is the predominant operating system for servers and is also used on all of the world's 500 fastest supercomputers.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] When combined with Android, which uses a Linux-based kernel and is designed for smartphones, they have the largest installed base of all general-purpose operating systems.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] The Linux kernel was created by Linus Torvalds, following the lack of a working kernel for GNU, a Unix-compatible operating system made entirely of free software that had been in development since 1983 by the GNU Project, led by Richard Stallman.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] A working Unix system called Minix was later released but its license was not entirely free at the time and it was made for education purposes.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] The first entirely free Unix for personal computers, 386BSD, did not appear until 1992, by which time Torvalds had already built and publicly released the first version of the Linux kernel on the Internet.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Like GNU and 386BSD, Linux did not have any Unix code, being a fresh re-implementation, and therefore avoided legal issues from AT&T.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Linux distributions became popular in the 1990s and made Unix technologies accessible to home users on personal computers whereas previously it had been confined to sophisticated workstations.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Desktop Linux distributions include a windowing system such as X11 or Wayland and a desktop environment such as KDE Plasma, GNOME, or Xfce.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Distributions intended for servers may not have a graphical user interface at all or include a solution stack such as LAMP.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] The source code of Linux may be used, modified, and distributed commercially or non-commercially by anyone under the terms of its respective licenses, such as the GNU General Public License (GPL).
[src:pacman-arch/linux] The license means creating novel distributions is permitted by anyone and is easier than it would be for an operating system such as macOS or Microsoft Windows.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] The Linux kernel, for example, is licensed under the GPLv2, with an exception for system calls that allows code that calls the kernel via system calls not to be licensed under the GPL.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Because of the dominance of Linux-based Android on smartphones, Linux, including Android, has the largest installed base of all general-purpose operating systems as of May 2022.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Linux is, as of March 2024, used by around 4 percent of desktop computers.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] The Chromebook, which runs the Linux kernel-based ChromeOS, dominates the US K–12 education market and represents nearly 20 percent of sub-$300 notebook sales in the US.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Linux also runs on embedded systems, i.e., devices whose operating system is typically built into the firmware and is highly tailored to the system.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] This includes routers, automation controls, smart home devices, video game consoles, televisions (Samsung and LG smart TVs), automobiles (Tesla, Audi, Mercedes-Benz, Hyundai, and Toyota), and spacecraft (Falcon 9 rocket, Dragon crew capsule, and the Ingenuity Mars helicopter).
[src:pacman-arch/linux] The Unix operating system was conceived of and implemented in 1969, at AT&T's Bell Labs in the United States, by Ken Thompson, Dennis Ritchie, Douglas McIlroy, and Joe Ossanna.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] First released in 1971, Unix was written entirely in assembly language, as was common practice at the time.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] In 1973, in a key pioneering approach, it was rewritten in the C programming language by Dennis Ritchie (except for some hardware and I/O routines).
[src:pacman-arch/linux] The availability of a high-level language implementation of Unix made its porting to different computer platforms easier.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] As a 1956 antitrust case forbade AT&T from entering the computer business, AT&T provided the operating system's source code to anyone who asked.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] As a result, Unix use grew quickly and it became widely adopted by academic institutions and businesses.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] In 1984, AT&T divested itself of its regional operating companies, and was released from its obligation not to enter the computer business; freed of that obligation, Bell Labs began selling Unix as a proprietary product, where users were not legally allowed to modify it.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Onyx Systems began selling early microcomputer-based Unix workstations in 1980.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Later, Sun Microsystems, founded as a spin-off of a student project at Stanford University, also began selling Unix-based desktop workstations in 1982.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] While Sun workstations did not use commodity PC hardware, for which Linux was later originally developed, it represented the first successful commercial attempt at distributing a primarily single-user microcomputer that ran a Unix operating system.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] With Unix increasingly "locked in" as a proprietary product, the GNU Project, started in 1983 by Richard Stallman, had the goal of creating a "complete Unix-compatible software system" composed entirely of free software.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Later, in 1985, Stallman started the Free Software Foundation and wrote the GNU General Public License (GNU GPL) in 1989.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Tanenbaum, a computer science professor, and released in 1987 as a minimal Unix-like operating system targeted at students and others who wanted to learn operating system principles.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Although the complete source code of Minix was freely available, the licensing terms prevented it from being free software until the licensing changed in April 2000.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] While attending the University of Helsinki in the fall of 1990, Torvalds enrolled in a Unix course.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] The course used a MicroVAX minicomputer running Ultrix, and one of the required texts was *Operating Systems: Design and Implementation* by Andrew S.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] This textbook included a copy of Tanenbaum's Minix operating system.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] It was with this course that Torvalds first became exposed to Unix.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] In 1991, he became curious about operating systems.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Frustrated by the licensing of Minix, which at the time limited it to educational use only, he began to work on his operating system kernel, which eventually became the Linux kernel.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] On 3 July 1991, to implement Unix system calls, Linus Torvalds attempted unsuccessfully to obtain a digital copy of the POSIX standards documentation with a request to the *comp.os.minix* newsgroup.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] After not finding the POSIX documentation, Torvalds initially resorted to determining system calls from SunOS documentation owned by the university for use in operating its Sun Microsystems server.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] He also learned some system calls from Tanenbaum's Minix text.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Torvalds began the development of the Linux kernel on Minix and applications written for Minix were also used on Linux.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Later, Linux matured and further Linux kernel development took place on Linux systems.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Torvalds initiated a switch from his original license, which prohibited commercial redistribution, to the GNU GPL.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Developers worked to integrate GNU components with the Linux kernel, creating a fully functional and free operating system.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Although not released until 1992, due to legal complications, the development of 386BSD, from which NetBSD, OpenBSD and FreeBSD descended, predated that of Linux.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Linus Torvalds has stated that if the GNU kernel or 386BSD had been available in 1991, he probably would not have created Linux.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] The Linux kernel is licensed under the GNU General Public License (GPL), version 2.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] The GPL requires that anyone who distributes software based on source code under this license must make the originating source code (and any modifications) available to the recipient under the same terms.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Torvalds states that the Linux kernel will not move from version 2 of the GPL to version 3.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] He specifically dislikes some provisions in the new license which prohibit the use of the software in digital rights management.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] It would also be impractical to obtain permission from all the copyright holders, who number in the thousands.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] A 2001 study of Red Hat Linux 7.1 found that this distribution contained 30 million lines of source code.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Using the Constructive Cost Model, the study estimated that this distribution required about eight thousand person-years of development time.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] According to the study, if all this software had been developed by conventional proprietary means, it would have cost about US$1.86 billion to develop in 2024 in the United States.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Most of the source code (71%) was written in the C programming language, but many other languages were used, including C++, Lisp, assembly language, Perl, Python, Fortran, and various shell scripting languages.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Slightly over half of all lines of code were licensed under the GPL.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] The Linux kernel itself was 2.4 million lines of code, or 8% of the total.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] In a later study, the same analysis was performed for Debian version 4.0 (etch, which was released in 2007).
[src:pacman-arch/linux] This distribution contained close to 283 million lines of source code, and the study estimated that it would have required about seventy three thousand man-years and cost US$10.4 billion (in 2024 dollars) to develop by conventional means.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] In the United States, the name *Linux* is a trademark registered to Linus Torvalds.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Della Croce Jr. filed for the trademark *Linux*, and then demanded royalties from Linux distributors.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] In 1996, Torvalds and some affected organizations sued him to have the trademark assigned to Torvalds, and, in 1997, the case was settled.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] The licensing of the trademark has since been handled by the Linux Mark Institute (LMI).
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Torvalds has stated that he trademarked the name only to prevent someone else from using it.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] LMI originally charged a nominal sublicensing fee for use of the Linux name as part of trademarks, but later changed this in favor of offering a free, perpetual worldwide sublicense.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] The Free Software Foundation (FSF) prefers *GNU/Linux* as the name when referring to the operating system as a whole, because it considers Linux distributions to be variants of the GNU operating system initiated in 1983 by Richard Stallman, president of the FSF.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] The foundation explicitly takes no issue over the name Android for the Android OS, which is also an operating system based on the Linux kernel, as GNU is not a part of it.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] A minority of public figures and software projects other than Stallman and the FSF, notably distributions consisting of only free software, such as Debian (which had been sponsored by the FSF up to 1996), also use *GNU/Linux* when referring to the operating system as a whole.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Most media and common usage, however, refers to this family of operating systems simply as *Linux*, as do many large Linux distributions (for example, SUSE Linux and Red Hat Enterprise Linux).
[src:pacman-arch/linux] As of May 2011, about 8% to 13% of the lines of code of the Linux distribution Ubuntu (version "Natty") is made of GNU components (the range depending on whether GNOME is considered part of GNU); meanwhile, 6% is taken by the Linux kernel, increased to 9% when including its direct dependencies.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Linus Torvalds had wanted to call his invention "Freax", a portmanteau of "free", "freak", and "x" (as an allusion to Unix).
[src:pacman-arch/linux] During the start of his work on the system, some of the project's makefiles included the name "Freax" for about half a year.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Torvalds considered the name "Linux" but dismissed it as too egotistical.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] To facilitate development, the files were uploaded to the FTP server of FUNET in September 1991.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Ari Lemmke, Torvalds' coworker at the Helsinki University of Technology (HUT) who was one of the volunteer administrators for the FTP server at the time, did not think that "Freax" was a good name, so he named the project "Linux" on the server without consulting Torvalds.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Later, however, Torvalds consented to "Linux".
[src:pacman-arch/linux] According to a newsgroup post by Torvalds, the word "Linux" should be pronounced (/ˈlɪnʊks/ ⓘ *LIN-uuks*) with a short 'i' as in 'print' and 'u' as in 'put'.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] To further demonstrate how the word "Linux" should be pronounced, he included an audio guide with the kernel source code.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] However, in this recording, he pronounces Linux as */ˈlinʊks/* (*LEEN-uuks*) with a short but close front unrounded vowel, instead of a near-close near-front unrounded vowel as in his newsgroup post.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Commercial use began when Dell and IBM, followed by Hewlett-Packard, started offering Linux support to escape Microsoft's monopoly in the desktop operating system market.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Today, Linux systems are used throughout computing, from embedded systems to virtually all supercomputers, and have secured a place in server installations such as the popular LAMP application stack.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] The use of Linux distributions in home and enterprise desktops has been growing.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Linux distributions have also become popular in the netbook market, with many devices shipping with customized Linux distributions installed, and Google releasing their own ChromeOS designed for netbooks.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Linux's greatest success in the consumer market is perhaps the mobile device market, with Android being the dominant operating system on smartphones and very popular on tablets and, more recently, on wearables, and vehicles.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Linux gaming is also on the rise with Valve showing its support for Linux and rolling out SteamOS, its own gaming-oriented Linux distribution, which was later implemented in their Steam Deck platform.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Linux distributions have also gained popularity with various local and national governments, such as the federal government of Brazil.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Linus Torvalds is the lead maintainer for the Linux kernel and guides its development, while Greg Kroah-Hartman is the lead maintainer for the stable branch.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Zoë Kooyman is the executive director of the Free Software Foundation, which in turn supports the GNU components.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Finally, individuals and corporations develop third-party non-GNU components.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] These third-party components comprise a vast body of work and may include both kernel modules and user applications and libraries.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Linux vendors and communities combine and distribute the kernel, GNU components, and non-GNU components, with additional package management software in the form of Linux distributions.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Many quantitative studies of free/open-source software focus on topics including market share and reliability, with numerous studies specifically examining Linux.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] The Linux market is growing, and the Linux operating system market size is expected to see a growth of 19.2% by 2027, reaching $15.64 billion, compared to $3.89 billion in 2019.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Analysts project a Compound Annual Growth Rate (CAGR) of 13.7% between 2024 and 2032, culminating in a market size of US$34.90 billion by the latter year.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Analysts and proponents attribute the relative success of Linux to its security, reliability, low cost, and freedom from vendor lock-in.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] estimate that 96.55% of web servers run Linux, 1.73% run Windows, and 1.72% run FreeBSD.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] this estimate was based on the number of Linux servers sold by various companies, and did not include server hardware purchased separately that had Linux installed on it later.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] As of 2024, estimates suggest Linux accounts for at least 80% of the public cloud workload, partly thanks to its widespread use in platforms like Amazon Web Services (AWS), Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud Platform.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] ZDNet reports that 96.3% of the top one million web servers are running Linux.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] W3Techs states that Linux powers at least 39.2% of websites whose operating system is known, with other estimates saying 55%.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Android, which is based on the Linux kernel, has become the dominant operating system for smartphones.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] holding 28%, and the remaining 1% attributed to various niche platforms.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] For years, Linux has been the platform of choice in the film industry.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] According to the Linux Movies Group, more than 95% of the servers and desktops at large animation and visual effects companies use Linux.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Linux distributions have also gained popularity with various local and national governments.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] News of the Russian military creating its own Linux distribution has also surfaced, and has come to fruition as the G.H.ost Project.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] has gone to the extent of mandating that all state high schools run Linux on their computers.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] processor family to achieve technology independence.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] In Spain, some regions have developed their own Linux distributions, which are widely used in education and official institutions, like gnuLinEx in Extremadura and Guadalinex in Andalusia.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] have also taken steps toward the adoption of Linux.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] In April 2026 France ordered its ministries to begin to replace 2.5 million Windows desktops with Linux.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] , is based on a version of Fedora Linux.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Many developers of open-source software agree that the Linux kernel was not designed but rather evolved through natural selection.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Torvalds considers that although the design of Unix served as a scaffolding, "Linux grew with a lot of mutations – and because the mutations were less than random, they were faster and more directed than alpha-particles in DNA." Eric S.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Raymond considers Linux's revolutionary aspects to be social, not technical: before Linux, complex software was designed carefully by small groups, but "Linux evolved in a completely different way.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] From nearly the beginning, it was rather casually hacked on by huge numbers of volunteers coordinating only through the Internet.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] A Linux-based system is a modular Unix-like operating system, deriving much of its basic design from principles established in Unix during the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Such a system uses a monolithic kernel, the Linux kernel, which handles process control, networking, access to the peripherals, and file systems.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Device drivers are either integrated directly with the kernel or added as modules that are loaded while the system is running.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] The GNU userland is a key part of most systems based on the Linux kernel, with Android being a notable exception.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] The GNU Project also develops Bash, a popular CLI shell.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] The graphical user interface (or GUI) used by most Linux systems is built on top of an implementation of the X Window System.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] More recently, some of the Linux community has sought to move to using Wayland as the display server protocol, replacing X11.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Many other open-source software projects contribute to Linux systems.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] The user interface, also known as the shell, is either a command-line interface (CLI), a graphical user interface (GUI), or controls attached to the associated hardware, which is common for embedded systems.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] For desktop systems, the default user interface is usually graphical, although the CLI is commonly available through terminal emulator windows or on a separate virtual console.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] CLI shells are text-based user interfaces, which use text for both input and output.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] The dominant shell used in Linux is the Bourne-Again Shell (bash), originally developed for the GNU Project; other shells such as Zsh are also used.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Most low-level Linux components, including various parts of the userland, use the CLI exclusively.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] The CLI is particularly suited for automation of repetitive or delayed tasks and provides very simple inter-process communication.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] On desktop systems, the most popular user interfaces are the GUI shells, packaged together with extensive desktop environments, such as KDE Plasma, GNOME, MATE, Cinnamon, LXDE, Pantheon, and Xfce, though a variety of additional user interfaces exist.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Most popular user interfaces are based on the X Window System, often simply called "X" or "X11".
[src:pacman-arch/linux] It provides network transparency and permits a graphical application running on one system to be displayed on another where a user may interact with the application; however, certain extensions of the X Window System are not capable of working over the network.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Several X display servers exist, with the reference implementation, X.Org Server, being the most popular.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Several types of window managers exist for X11, including tiling, dynamic, stacking, and compositing.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Window managers provide means to control the placement and appearance of individual application windows, and interact with the X Window System.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Desktop environments include window managers as part of their standard installations, such as Mutter (GNOME), KWin (KDE), or Xfwm (xfce), although users may choose to use a different window manager if preferred.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Wayland is a display server protocol intended as a replacement for the X11 protocol; as of 2022, it has received relatively wide adoption.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Unlike X11, Wayland does not need an external window manager and compositing manager.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Therefore, a Wayland compositor takes the role of the display server, window manager, and compositing manager.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Weston is the reference implementation of Wayland, while GNOME's Mutter and KDE's KWin are being ported to Wayland as standalone display servers.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Enlightenment has already been successfully ported since version 19.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Additionally, many window managers have been made for Wayland, such as Sway or Hyprland, as well as other graphical utilities such as Waybar or Rofi.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Linux currently has two modern kernel-userspace APIs for handling video input devices: V4L2 API for video streams and radio, and DVB API for digital TV reception.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] The diversity of hardware standards and data formats requires continuous architectural refinement to maintain compatibility across different device classes.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Development focuses on providing robust userspace libraries to abstract device complexity, ensuring that applications can interface with varying formats without specialized hardware-specific drivers.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] The primary difference between Linux and many other popular contemporary operating systems is that the Linux kernel and other components are free and open-source software.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Linux is not the only such operating system, although it is by far the most widely used.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Some free and open-source software licenses are based on the principle of copyleft, a kind of reciprocity: any work derived from a copyleft piece of software must also be copyleft itself.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] The most common free software license, the GNU General Public License (GPL), is a form of copyleft and is used for the Linux kernel and many of the components from the GNU Project.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Linux-based distributions are intended by developers for interoperability with other operating systems and established computing standards.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Linux systems adhere to POSIX, Single UNIX Specification (SUS), Linux Standard Base (LSB), ISO, and ANSI standards where possible, although to date only one Linux distribution has been POSIX.1 certified, Linux-FT.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] The Open Group has tested and certified at least two Linux distributions as qualifying for the Unix trademark, EulerOS and Inspur K-UX.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Free software projects, although developed through collaboration, are often produced independently of each other.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] The fact that the software licenses explicitly permit redistribution, however, provides a basis for larger-scale projects that collect the software produced by stand-alone projects and make it available all at once in the form of a Linux distribution.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Many Linux distributions manage a remote collection of system software and application software packages available for download and installation through a network connection.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] This allows users to adapt the operating system to their specific needs.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Distributions are maintained by individuals, loose-knit teams, volunteer organizations, and commercial entities.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] A distribution is responsible for the default configuration of the installed Linux kernel, general system security, and more generally integration of the different software packages into a coherent whole.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Distributions typically use a package manager such as apt, yum, zypper, pacman or portage to install, remove, and update all of a system's software from one central location.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] A distribution is largely driven by its developer and user communities.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Some vendors develop and fund their distributions on a volunteer basis, Debian being a well-known example.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Others maintain a community version of their commercial distributions, as Red Hat does with Fedora, and SUSE does with openSUSE.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] In many cities and regions, local associations known as Linux User Groups (LUGs) seek to promote their preferred distribution and by extension free software.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] They hold meetings and provide free demonstrations, training, technical support, and operating system installation to new users.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Many Internet communities also provide support to Linux users and developers.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Most distributions and free software / open-source projects have IRC chatrooms or newsgroups.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Online forums are another means of support, with notable examples being Unix & Linux Stack Exchange, LinuxQuestions.org and the various distribution-specific support and community forums, such as ones for Ubuntu, Fedora, Arch Linux, Gentoo, etc.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Linux distributions host mailing lists; commonly there will be a specific topic such as usage or development for a given list.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] There are several technology websites with a Linux focus.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Print magazines on Linux often bundle cover disks that carry software or even complete Linux distributions.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Although Linux distributions are generally available without charge, several large corporations sell, support, and contribute to the development of the components of the system and free software.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] An analysis of the Linux kernel in 2017 showed that well over 85% of the code was developed by programmers who are being paid for their work, leaving about 8.2% to unpaid developers and 4.1% unclassified.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Some of the major corporations that provide contributions include Intel, Samsung, Google, AMD, Oracle, and Facebook.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Several corporations, notably Red Hat, Canonical, and SUSE have built a significant business around Linux distributions.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] The free software licenses, on which the various software packages of a distribution built on the Linux kernel are based, explicitly accommodate and encourage commercialization; the relationship between a Linux distribution as a whole and individual vendors may be seen as symbiotic.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] One common business model of commercial suppliers is charging for support, especially for business users.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] A number of companies also offer a specialized business version of their distribution, which adds proprietary support packages and tools to administer higher numbers of installations or to simplify administrative tasks.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Another business model is to give away the software to sell hardware.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] This used to be the norm in the computer industry, with operating systems such as CP/M, Apple DOS, and versions of the classic Mac OS before 7.6 freely copyable (but not modifiable).
[src:pacman-arch/linux] As computer hardware standardized throughout the 1980s, it became more difficult for hardware manufacturers to profit from this tactic, as the OS would run on any manufacturer's computer that shared the same architecture.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Most programming languages support Linux either directly or through third-party community based ports.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] The original development tools used for building both Linux applications and operating system programs are found within the GNU toolchain, which includes the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) and the GNU Build System.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Among others, GCC provides compilers for Ada, C, C++, Go and Fortran.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Many programming languages have a cross-platform reference implementation that supports Linux, for example PHP, Perl, Ruby, Python, Java, Go, Rust and Haskell.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] First released in 2003, the LLVM project provides an alternative cross-platform open-source compiler for many languages.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Proprietary compilers for Linux include the Intel C++ Compiler, Sun Studio, and IBM XL C/C++ Compiler.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] BASIC is available in procedural form from QB64, PureBasic, Yabasic, GLBasic, Basic4GL, XBasic, wxBasic, SdlBasic, and Basic-256, and in object oriented through Gambas, FreeBASIC, B4X, Basic for Qt, Phoenix Object Basic, NS Basic, ProvideX, Chipmunk Basic, RapidQ and Xojo.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Pascal is implemented through GNU Pascal, Free Pascal, Virtual Pascal, and graphically via Lazarus, PascalABC.NET, or Delphi using FireMonkey (formerly through Borland Kylix).
[src:pacman-arch/linux] A common feature of Unix-like systems, Linux includes traditional specific-purpose programming languages targeted at scripting, text processing and system configuration and management in general.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Linux distributions support shell scripts, AWK, sed and make.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Many programs also have an embedded programming language to support configuring or programming themselves.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] For example, regular expressions are supported in programs like grep and locate, the traditional Unix message transfer agent Sendmail contains its own Turing complete scripting system, and the advanced text editor GNU Emacs is built around a general purpose Lisp interpreter.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Most distributions also include support for PHP, Perl, Ruby, Python and other dynamic languages.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] While not as common, Linux also supports C# and other CLI languages (via Mono), Vala, and Scheme.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Many Java virtual machines and development kits run on Linux, including the original Sun Microsystems JVM (HotSpot), IBM's J2SE RE, and many open-source projects like Kaffe and Jikes RVM; Kotlin, Scala, Groovy and other JVM languages are also available.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] GNOME and KDE are popular desktop environments and provide a framework for developing applications.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] These projects are based on the GTK and Qt widget toolkits, respectively, which can also be used independently of the larger framework.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Both support a wide variety of languages.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] There are a number of Integrated development environments available including Anjuta, Code::Blocks, CodeLite, Eclipse, Geany, ActiveState Komodo, KDevelop, Lazarus, MonoDevelop, NetBeans, and Qt Creator, while the long-established editors Vim, nano and Emacs remain popular.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] A topic of perennial discussion is the area of graphic design on Linux.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Typical common graphics and image tools are programs such as: GNU Image Manipulation Program (GIMP), Inkscape, Krita, DaVinci Resolve, and Scribus.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] The Linux kernel is a widely ported operating system kernel, available for devices ranging from mobile phones to supercomputers; it runs on a highly diverse range of computer architectures, including ARM-based Android smartphones and the IBM Z mainframes.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Specialized distributions and kernel forks exist for less mainstream architectures; for example, the ELKS kernel fork can run on Intel 8086 or Intel 80286 16-bit microprocessors, while the μClinux kernel fork may run on systems without a memory management unit.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] The kernel also runs on architectures that were only ever intended to use a proprietary manufacturer-created operating system, such as Macintosh computers (with PowerPC, Intel, and Apple silicon processors), PDAs, video game consoles, portable music players, and mobile phones.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Linux has a reputation for supporting old hardware very well by maintaining standardized drivers for a long time.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] There are several industry associations and hardware conferences devoted to maintaining and improving support for diverse hardware under Linux, such as FreedomHEC.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Over time, support for different hardware has improved in Linux, resulting in any off-the-shelf purchase having a "good chance" of being compatible.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] In 2014, a new initiative was launched to automatically collect a database of all tested hardware configurations.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] One commonly expressed attribute about Linux (or open source software in general) is that through regular vetting by many individuals the software is progressively made more secure, a process referred to as being called "Linus's law".
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Linux is often highlighted for its share of the estimated global servers market share.
[src:pacman-arch/linux] Besides many volunteers, the not-for-profit bodies such as the Open Source Security Foundation and Linux Foundation actively pursue ways to promote security in the Linux platform as well.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] A **package manager**, or **package management system**, is software that supports installing, upgrading, configuring, and removing software for the host system in a consistent manner.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] A package manager deals with *packages*, distributions of software and data in archive files.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Packages contain metadata, such as the software's name, description of its purpose, version number, vendor, checksum (usually a cryptographic hash function), and a list of dependencies necessary for the software to run properly.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Upon installation, metadata is stored in a local package database.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Package managers typically maintain a database of software dependencies and version information to prevent software mismatches and missing prerequisites.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] They work closely with software repositories, binary repository managers, and app stores.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Package managers are designed to eliminate the need for manual installs and updates.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] This can be particularly useful for large enterprises whose operating systems (OSes) typically consist of hundreds or even tens of thousands of distinct packages.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] An early package manager was SMIT (and its backend install) from IBM AIX.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] SMIT was introduced with AIX 3.0 in 1989.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Package managers like dpkg have existed as early as 1994.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Early package managers, from around 1994, had no automatic dependency resolution but could already simplify the process of adding and removing software from a running system.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] By around 1995, beginning with CPAN, package managers began handling package repository downloads, and dependency resolution and installation as needed, making it easier to install, uninstall and update software.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] A software package is an archive file containing a computer program as well as necessary metadata for its deployment.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] The program may be in source code that has to be compiled and built first.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Package metadata include the software's description, version number, and dependencies.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Package managers are charged with the task of finding, installing, maintaining or uninstalling packages upon the user's command.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Computer systems that rely on dynamic library linking, instead of static library linking, share executable libraries of machine instructions across packages and applications.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] In these systems, conflicting relationships between different packages requiring different versions of libraries results in a situation called *dependency hell*.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] On Microsoft Windows systems, this is also called *DLL hell* when working with dynamically-linked libraries.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Modern package managers have mostly solved these problems by allowing parallel installation of multiple library versions (e.g.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] OPENSTEP's *Framework* system), a dependency of any kind (e.g.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] *slots* in Gentoo Portage), and even packages compiled with different compiler versions (e.g. dynamic libraries built by the Glasgow Haskell Compiler, where a stable ABI does not exist), in order to enable other packages to specify which version they are linked or installed against.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] System administrators may install and maintain software using tools other than package managers.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] For example, a local administrator may download unpackaged source code, compile it, and install it.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] This may cause the local system to fall out of synchronization with the package manager's database.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] The local administrator will be required to take additional measures, such as manually managing some dependencies or integrating the changes into the package manager.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] There are tools to ensure that locally-compiled packages are integrated with the package management.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Upgrades of configuration files may be particularly troublesome.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Since package managers, at least on Unix systems, originated as extensions of file archivers, they can usually only overwrite or retain configuration files, rather than apply rules to them.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] There are exceptions to this that usually apply to kernel configuration (which, if broken, will render the computer unusable after a restart).
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Problems can be caused if the configuration file format changes; for instance, if the old file does not explicitly disable new options that should be disabled.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Some package managers, such as Debian's dpkg, allow configuration during installation.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] In other situations, packages are installed with the default configuration, which is then overwritten, for example in headless installations to a large number of computers.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] This kind of pre-configured installation is also supported by dpkg.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] To give users more control over the software they allow to be installed on their systems, and sometimes due to legal or convenience reasons on the distributors' side, packages are often downloaded from software repositories.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Many package managers can be configured to never upgrade certain packages, or to upgrade them only when critical vulnerabilities or instabilities are found in the previous version, as defined by the packager of the software.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] This process is called *upgrade suppression*, or *version pinning*.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Some of the more advanced package management features offer *cascading package removal*, in which all packages that depend on the target package and all packages that only it depends on are also removed.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Although commands are specific to each package manager, they are translatable to a large extent, as most package managers offer similar functions.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] The Arch Linux wiki offers an extensive overview of commands.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Linux distributions oriented to binary packages rely heavily on package management systems as their primary means of managing and maintaining software.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Mobile operating systems such as Android (Linux-based) and iOS (Unix-based) rely almost exclusively on their respective vendors' app stores and thus use their own dedicated package management systems.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] A package manager is often called an *install manager*, which can lead to a confusion between package managers and installers.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Most software configuration management systems treat building software and deploying software as separate, independent steps.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] A build automation utility typically takes human-readable source code files already on a computer, and automates the process of converting them into an executable package on the same or a remote computer.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Later, a package manager typically running on another computer downloads the pre-built executable and installs it.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] A few tools, such as Maak and A-A-P, are designed to handle both building and deployment, and can be used as either build automation utilities, package managers, or both.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] App stores can also be considered application-level package managers (without the ability to install all levels of programs).
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Unlike traditional package managers, app stores are designed to enable payment for the software itself (instead of for software development), and may only offer monolithic packages with no dependencies or dependency resolution.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] They are usually limited in their management functionality, due to focusing on ease-of-use over power or emergence, and are common in commercial operating systems and smart devices.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Package managers also often have only human-reviewed code.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Many app stores, such as Google Play and Apple's App Store, mainly screen apps using automated tools only; malware can pass these tests by detecting when the app is being tested, and delaying malicious activity.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] There are exceptions: the npm package database, for instance, relies entirely on post-publication review of its code, while the Debian package database has an extensive human review process before any package goes into the main database.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] The XZ Utils backdoor used years of trust-building to insert a backdoor, which was nonetheless caught while in the testing database.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Also known as binary repository manager, it is a software tool designed to optimize the download and storage of binary files, artifacts and packages used and produced in the software development process.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] These package managers aim to standardize the way enterprises treat all package types.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] They give users the ability to apply security and compliance metrics across all artifact types.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Universal package managers have been referred to as being at the center of a DevOps toolchain.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Each package manager relies on the format and metadata of the packages in its repository.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] That is, package managers need groups of files to be bundled along with appropriate metadata, such as dependencies.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Often, a core set of utilities manages the basic installation from these packages and multiple package managers use these utilities to provide additional functionality.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] For example, yum relies on rpm as a backend.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Yum extends the functionality of rpm by adding features such as simple configuration for maintaining a network of systems.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] As another example, the Synaptic Package Manager provides a graphical user interface by using the Advanced Packaging Tool (apt) library, which in turn relies on dpkg for core functionality.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Alien is a program that converts between different Linux package formats, supporting conversion between Linux Standard Base (LSB) compliant .rpm packages, .deb, Stampede (.slp), Solaris (.pkg) and Slackware (.tgz, .txz, .tbz, .tlz) packages.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] For mobile operating systems, Google Play uses the Android application package (APK) package format while Microsoft Store uses the APPX and XAP formats.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Both Google Play and Microsoft Store have eponymous package managers.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] By the nature of free and open-source software (FOSS), packages under similar and compatible licenses are available on a number of operating systems.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] These packages can be combined and distributed using configurable packaging systems to handle many permutations of software and manage version-specific dependencies and conflicts.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Some managers of FOSS packages are released as FOSS themselves.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] The ability to continuously upgrade third-party software is typically added by adding the URL of the corresponding repository to the package management's configuration file.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Besides system-level application managers, there are add-on package managers for operating systems with limited capabilities and for programming languages in which developers need the latest libraries.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Unlike system-level package managers, application-level package managers focus on a small part of the software system.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] They typically reside within a directory tree that is not maintained by the system-level manager, such as c:\cygwin or /opt/sw.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] This may not be the case for managers that deal with programming libraries, leading to possible conflicts, as both managers may claim to own a file and may break upgrades.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] Ian Murdock commented that package management is "the single biggest advancement Linux has brought to the industry", that it blurs the boundaries between operating systems and applications, and that it makes it "easier to push new innovations [...] into the marketplace and [...] evolve the OS".
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] There is also a conference for package manager developers known as PackagingCon.
[src:pacman-arch/package-manager] It was established in 2021 with the aim to understand different approaches to package management.
