[src:pacman-arch/pacman-conf] Alternatively, you can get more fine-grained control by combining some of the options and prefixes described below.
[src:pacman-arch/pacman-conf] All options in a config file are processed in top-to-bottom, left-to-right fashion, where later options override and/or supplement earlier ones.
[src:pacman-arch/pacman-conf] If *SigLevel* is specified in a repository section, the starting value is that from the [options] section, or the built-in system default as shown below if not specified.
[src:pacman-arch/pacman-conf] The options are split into two main groups, described below.
[src:pacman-arch/pacman-conf] Terms used such as “marginally trusted” are terms used by GnuPG, for more information please consult gpg(1).
[src:pacman-arch/pacman-conf] These options control if and when signature checks should take place.
[src:pacman-arch/pacman-conf] All signature checking is suppressed, even if signatures are present.
[src:pacman-arch/pacman-conf] Signatures are checked if present; absence of a signature is not an error.
[src:pacman-arch/pacman-conf] An invalid signature is a fatal error, as is a signature from a key not in the keyring.
[src:pacman-arch/pacman-conf] Signatures are required; absence of a signature or an invalid signature is a fatal error, as is a signature from a key not in the keyring.
[src:pacman-arch/pacman-conf] These options control what signatures are viewed as permissible.
[src:pacman-arch/pacman-conf] Note that neither of these options allows acceptance of invalid or expired signatures, or those from revoked keys.
[src:pacman-arch/pacman-conf] If a signature is checked, it must be in the keyring and fully trusted; marginal trust does not meet this criteria.
[src:pacman-arch/pacman-conf] If a signature is checked, it must be in the keyring, but is not required to be assigned a trust level (e.g., unknown or marginal trust).
[src:pacman-arch/pacman-conf] Options in both groups can additionally be prefixed with either **Package** or **Database**, which will cause it to only take effect on the specified object type.
[src:pacman-arch/pacman-conf] For example, PackageTrustAll would allow marginal and unknown trust level signatures for packages.
[src:pacman-arch/pacman-conf] If you have numerous custom packages of your own, it is often easier to generate your own custom local repository than install them all with the *--upgrade* option.
