[src:pacman-arch/pacman-conf] Pacman will now use your package repository.
[src:pacman-arch/pacman-conf] If you add new packages to the repository, remember to re-generate the database and use pacman’s *--refresh* option.
[src:pacman-arch/pacman-conf] For more information on the repo-add command, see “repo-add --help” or repo-add(8).
[src:pacman-arch/pacman-rosetta] This page uses a table to display the correspondence of package management commands among some of the most popular Linux distributions.
[src:pacman-arch/pacman-rosetta] The original inspiration was given by openSUSE's Software Management Command Line Comparison.
[src:pacman-arch/pacman-rosetta] , a simple wrapper around other package managers.
[src:pacman-arch/pacman-rosetta] By default, Arch Linux does not rotate `pacman.log`.
[src:pacman-arch/pacman-rosetta] This is in contrast to the default policy of most other Linux distributions.
[src:pacman-arch/pacman-rosetta] Some distributions, notably Gentoo, hardly write log files by default.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] The pacman package manager is one of the major distinguishing features of Arch Linux.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] It combines a simple binary package format with an easy-to-use Arch build system.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] The goal of *pacman* is to make it possible to easily manage packages, whether they are from the official repositories or the user's own builds.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] What follows is just a small sample of the operations that *pacman* can perform.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] To read more examples, refer to pacman(8).
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Arch's package manager *pacman* can install, update, and remove those packages.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] , as the former could lead to dependency issues.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] The same command can be used to reinstall a package.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Sometimes there are multiple versions of a package in different repositories (e.g.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] To install a number of packages sharing similar patterns in their names, one can use curly brace expansion.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] A virtual package is a special package which does not exist by itself, but is provided by one or more other packages.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Virtual packages allow other packages to not name a specific package as a dependency, in case there are several candidates.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Virtual packages cannot be installed by their name, instead they become installed in your system when you have installed a package *providing* the virtual package.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] , then alphabetically when multiple results exist from the same repository.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Some packages belong to a group of packages that can all be installed simultaneously.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] will prompt you to select the packages from the gnome group that you wish to install.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Sometimes a package group will contain a large amount of packages, and there may be only a few that you do or do not want to install.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] which will select all packages except 5 through 8 and 2 for installation.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Also visit https://archlinux.org/groups/ to see what package groups are available.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] If a package in the list is already installed on the system, it will be reinstalled even if it is already up-to-date.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] , this ignores the install reason of the packages in the group, because it acts as though each package in the group is listed separately.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Install reason of dependencies is still respected.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] The above may sometimes refuse to run when removing a group which contains otherwise needed packages.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] This operation is recursive, and must be used with care since it can remove many potentially needed packages.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] The following operation can break a system and should be avoided.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] will not remove configurations that the application itself creates (for example "dotfiles" in the home directory).
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Passing the `k` flag twice will perform a more thorough check.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] See pacman/Tips and tricks for more examples.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] For advanced functionality, install pkgfile, which uses a separate database with all files and their associated packages.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Install the pacman-contrib package to get pactree(8).
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] To view the dependent tree of a package, pass the reverse flag `-r` to *pactree*.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] The *pacman* databases are normally located at `/var/lib/pacman/sync`.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] For each repository specified in `/etc/pacman.conf`, there will be a corresponding database file located there.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] The `desc` file contains meta data such as the package description, dependencies, file size and MD5 hash.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] A package that has been uninstalled can easily be reinstalled directly from the cache directory, without requiring a new download from the repository.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] However, it is necessary to deliberately clean up the cache periodically to prevent the directory from growing indefinitely in size.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Enable and start `paccache.timer` to discard unused packages weekly.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] You can configure the arguments for the service in `/etc/conf.d/pacman-contrib`, e.g with `PACCACHE_ARGS='-k1'` or `PACCACHE_ARGS='-uk0'` for the two examples below.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] You can also define how many recent versions you want to keep.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Add the `-u`/`--uninstalled` switch to limit the action of *paccache* to uninstalled packages.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] One should avoid deleting from the cache all past versions of installed packages and all uninstalled packages unless one desperately needs to free some disk space.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] This will prevent downgrading or reinstalling packages without downloading them again.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] pkgcachecleanAUR and pacleanerAUR are two further alternatives to clean the cache.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] To get a list in a processable format, and to prevent the actions of `-S`, `-U` and `-R`, you can use `-p`, short for `--print`.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] `--print-format` can be added to format this list in various ways.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] `--print-format %n` will return a list without package versions.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] The command is normally used because explicitly-installed packages may offer optional packages, usually for non-essential features for which the user has discretion.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] will also remove optional packages set this way.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] When **re**installing a package, though, the current installation reason is preserved by default.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] The list of explicitly-installed packages can be shown with `pacman -Qe`, while the complementary list of dependencies can be shown with `pacman -Qd`.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Use `--asexplicit` to do the opposite operation.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] This would change the installation reason of not only the package being installed, but also the packages being upgraded.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Choose which packages will be added or removed in the transaction.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Prepare the transaction, based on flags, by performing sanity checks on the sync databases, packages, and their dependencies.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] If pre-existing *pacman* `PreTransaction` hooks apply, they are executed.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Packages are removed that are to-be-replaced, conflicting, or explicitly targeted to be removed.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] *pacman* deletes all the files from a pre-existing version of the package (in the case of an upgraded or removed package).
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] However, files that were marked as configuration files in the package are kept (see /Pacnew and Pacsave).
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] *pacman* untars the package and dumps its files into the file system (in the case of an installed or upgraded package).
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Files that would overwrite kept, and manually modified, configuration files (see previous step), are stored with a new name (*.pacnew*).
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] If the package has an install script, its `post_install` function is executed (or `post_upgrade` or `post_remove` in the case of an upgraded or removed package).
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] If *pacman* `PostTransaction` hooks that exist at the end of the transaction apply, they are executed.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Release the transaction and transaction resource (i.e. database lock).
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] General options are in the `[options]` section.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Read pacman.conf(5) or look in the default `pacman.conf` for information on what can be done here.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] To see old and new versions of available packages, uncomment the "VerbosePkgLists" line in `/etc/pacman.conf`.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] The number of packages being downloaded in parallel (at the same time) are configured in `/etc/pacman.conf` with the `ParallelDownloads` option under `[options]`.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] The `/etc/pacman.conf` shipped with the pacman package sets it to `5`.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] If the option is unset, packages will be downloaded sequentially.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] For multiple packages use a space-separated list, or use additional `IgnorePkg` lines.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] If you want to skip packages just once, you can also use the `--ignore` option on the command-line - this time with a comma-separated list.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] It will still be possible to upgrade the ignored packages using `pacman -S`: in this case *pacman* will remind you that the packages have been included in an `IgnorePkg` statement.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] All files listed with a `NoUpgrade` directive will never be touched during a package install/upgrade, and the new files will be installed with a *.pacnew* extension.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] The path refers to files in the package archive.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Therefore, do not include the leading slash.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] To always skip installation of specific files or directories list them under `NoExtract`.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Later rules override previous ones, and you can negate a rule by prepending `!`.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] where `*/path/to/common/settings*` file contains the same options for both configurations.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] For more information on alpm hooks, see alpm-hooks(5).
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Besides the special [options] section, each other `[section]` in `pacman.conf` defines a package repository to be used.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] A *repository* is a *logical* collection of packages, which are *physically* stored on one or more servers: for this reason each server is called a *mirror* for the repository.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Repositories are distinguished between official and unofficial.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] The order of repositories in the configuration file matters; repositories listed first will take precedence over those listed later in the file when packages in two repositories have identical names, regardless of version number.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] In order to use a repository after adding it, you will need to upgrade the whole system first.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Each repository section allows defining the list of its mirrors directly or in a dedicated external file through the `Include` directive; for example, the mirrors for the official repositories are included from `/etc/pacman.d/mirrorlist`.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] See the Mirrors article for mirror configuration.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Cache directory may grow over time, even if keeping just the freshest versions of installed packages.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] This is happening because *pacman* has detected a file conflict, and by design, will not overwrite files for you.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] The problem is usually trivial to solve (although to be sure, you should try to find out how these files got there in the first place).
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] A safe way is to first check if another package owns the file (`pacman -Qo */path/to/file*`).
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] If the file is owned by another package, file a bug report.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] If the file is not owned by another package, rename the file which "exists in filesystem" and re-issue the update command.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] If all goes well, the file may then be removed.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] If you had installed a program manually without using *pacman*, for example through `make install`, you have to remove/uninstall this program with all of its files.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] See also Pacman tips#Identify files not owned by any package.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Every installed package provides a `/var/lib/pacman/local/*package-version*/files` file that contains metadata about this package.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] If this file gets corrupted, is empty or goes missing, it results in `file exists in filesystem` errors when trying to update the package.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Such an error usually concerns only one package.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Instead of manually renaming and later removing all the files that belong to the package in question, you may explicitly run `pacman -S --overwrite *glob* *package*` to force *pacman* to overwrite files that match `*glob*`.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Look for *.part* files (partially downloaded packages) in `/var/cache/pacman/pkg/` and remove them (often caused by usage of a custom `XferCommand` in `pacman.conf`).
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] That same error may also appear if *archlinux-keyring* is out-of-date, preventing *pacman* from verifying signatures.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] See Pacman/Package signing#Upgrade system regularly for the fix and how to avoid it in the future.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] When *pacman* is about to alter the package database, for example installing a package, it creates a lock file at `/var/lib/pacman/db.lck`.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] This prevents another instance of *pacman* from trying to alter the package database at the same time.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] If *pacman* is interrupted while changing the database, this stale lock file can remain.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] as root to verify if there is any process still using it.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] This error manifests as `Not found in sync db`, `Target not found` or `Failed retrieving file`.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Firstly, ensure the package actually exists.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] If certain the package exists, your package list may be out-of-date.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Try running `pacman -Syu` to force a refresh of all package lists and upgrade.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Also make sure the selected mirrors are up-to-date and repositories are correctly configured.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] You can also use Reflector to keep the mirrors up-to-date.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] If *pacman* reports there is nothing to update, but the `Failed retrieving file` error continues to be printed, consider forcing a database download with `pacman -Syyu`.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] This is never needed under normal circumstances, so inspect more closely the status and consistency of the mirror.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] It could also be that the repository containing the package is not enabled on your system, e.g. the package could be in the multilib repository, but *multilib* is not enabled in your `pacman.conf`.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] See also FAQ#Why is there only a single version of each shared library in the official repositories?.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Whether due to power loss, kernel panic or hardware failure an update may be interrupted.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] In most cases, there will not be much damage but the system will likely be unbootable.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Mount the root filesystem as well as your ESP.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] `arch-chroot` into the mounted root filesystem.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Replicating the *exact* upgrade is needed to ensure the right scriptlets and hooks will run.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] If the system uses default database and directory locations, you can now update the system's *pacman* database and upgrade it via `pacman --root=/mnt --cachedir=/mnt/var/cache/pacman/pkg -Syu` as root.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Followed by a re-install of any still broken package via `pacman --root /mnt --cachedir=/mnt/var/cache/pacman/pkg -S *package*`.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] If `/var/cache/pacman/pkg` is a symlink, *pacman* will try to make a directory instead and thus remove this symlink during self-upgrade.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] As a result, `/usr/bin/pacman` and other contents of the pacman package will be missing.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Never symlink `/var/cache/pacman/pkg` because it is controlled by *pacman*.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Use the `CacheDir` option or a bind mount instead; see #Package cache directory.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] If you have already encountered this problem and broke your system, you can manually extract `/usr` contents from the package to restore *pacman* and then reinstall it properly; see FS#73306 and related forum thread for details.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] pacman-staticAUR is a statically compiled version of *pacman*, so it will be able to run even when the libraries on the system are not working.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] This can also come in handy when a partial upgrade was performed and *pacman* can not run anymore.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] In some situations, your system may be too broken to run *makepkg* or to build the pacman-staticAUR package (e.g., due to missing or incompatible libraries).
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] In this case, you can download a precompiled *pacman-static* binary from a trusted source.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] This static binary does not depend on system libraries and can be used to restore a working *pacman* on your system.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] This will update your system and reinstall pacman, fixing broken dependencies related to missing shared libraries.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] If even *pacman-static* does not work, it is possible to recover using an external *pacman*.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] One of the easiest methods to do so is by using the archiso and simply using `--sysroot` or `--root` to specify the mount point of the system to perform the operation on.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] See Chroot#Using chroot on how to mount the necessary filesystems required by `--sysroot`.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] It is extremely easy to break your system even worse using this approach.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Even if *pacman* is terribly broken, you can fix it manually by downloading the latest packages and extracting them to the correct locations.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] But you may only need to update a few of them depending on your issue.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Note the use of the `w` flag for interactive mode.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Running non-interactively is very risky since you might end up overwriting an important file.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Also take care to extract packages in the correct order (i.e. dependencies first).
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] This forum post contains an example of this process where only a couple *pacman* dependencies are broken.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Most likely the initramfs became corrupted during a kernel update (improper use of *pacman'*s `--overwrite` option can be a cause).
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] There are two options; first, try the *Fallback* entry.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] If that does not work, from a current Arch release (CD/DVD or USB stick), mount your root and boot partitions to `/mnt` and `/mnt/boot`, respectively.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Reinstalling the kernel (the linux package) will automatically re-generate the initramfs image with `mkinitcpio -p linux`.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Afterwards, it is recommended that you run `exit`, `umount /mnt/{boot,}` and `reboot`.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] As the error message says, your locale is not correctly configured.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] When locale files are intentionally removed by tools such as bleachbit or localepurgeAUR, `pacman` may issue warnings about missing locales during package updates.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] To suppress these warnings, you can comment out the `CheckSpace` option in `pacman.conf`.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Keep in mind that disabling CheckSpace turns off the space-checking functionality for all package installations, so use this workaround only when you have alternative means to monitor disk space.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Make sure that the relevant environment variables (`$http_proxy`, `$ftp_proxy` etc.) are set up.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] If you use *pacman* with sudo, you need to configure sudo to pass these environment variables to pacman.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Also, ensure the configuration of dirmngr has `honor-http-proxy` in `/etc/pacman.d/gnupg/dirmngr.conf` to honor the proxy when refreshing the keys.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] To reinstall all the native packages: `pacman -Qnq | pacman -S -` or `pacman -S $(pacman -Qnq)` (the `-S` option preserves the installation reason by default).
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] You will then need to reinstall all the foreign packages, which can be listed with `pacman -Qmq`.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] It looks like previous *pacman* transaction removed or corrupted shared libraries needed for *pacman* itself.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] To recover from this situation, you need to unpack required libraries to your filesystem manually.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] First find what package contains the missed library and then locate it in the *pacman* cache (`/var/cache/pacman/pkg/`).
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Unpack required shared library to the filesystem.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Now you need to reinstall the broken package.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Note that you need to use `--overwrite` flag as you just unpacked system files and *pacman* does not know about it.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] *pacman* will correctly replace our shared library file with one from package.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] When installing Arch Linux as a guest OS in VirtualBox, this issue has also been addressed by using *Host interface* instead of *NAT* in the machine properties.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] If you receive this error message with correct mirrors, try setting a different name server.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] If you want to install a package on an sshfs mount using `pacman -U` and receive this error, move the package to a local directory and try to install again.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] This is frequently caused by the chroot directory not being a mountpoint when the chroot is entered.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] See the note at Install Arch Linux from existing Linux#Downloading basic tools for a solution, and arch-chroot(8) for an explanation and an example of using bind mounting to make the chroot directory a mountpoint.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] If you are unable to update packages and receive this error, then try `rm -r /var/lib/pacman/sync/` before attempting to update.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] If removing sync files does not help, check that the sync files are `gzip compressed data` using `file /var/lib/pacman/sync/*` before attempting to update.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] A router or proxy might corrupt the downloads.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] If sync files are of the correct type, there might be an issue with the mirror server.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Look up the mirror server(s) in use with `pacman-conf -r core` and `pacman-conf -r extra`.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Paste the first returned url in a browser and check that a file listing is returned.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] In case the mirror returns an error, comment it in `/etc/pacman.d/mirrorlist`.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] You may try updating or re-ranking mirrors.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] If this error occurs and you are, for instance, unable to update your system or any package at all, it is possible that you have `DISPLAY` set to a blank value, which seems to break the GPG-Flow.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] In this case, `unset DISPLAY` or setting it to a arbitrary value will most likely allow to update again, in case any other option above did not do the trick yet.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] One may use the `pacman -Qk $pkg` to check if the installed files of the `$pkg` package match the files from its database version.
[src:pacman-arch/title-pacman] Suppose that your local database located in `/var/lib/pacman` is more up-to-date compared to installed packages in the `/` filesystem (*e.g.*, because of a partial rollback), then this method is the appropriate one to re-synchronize the root filesystem with the local database.
